text: ‚ÄúBridge of Spies‚Äù is one of the best films this year. The film opens with a shot of a man looking in a mirror as he paints a nearly-complete self-portrait, which sets the intriguing pace for of this true story and a brilliant film. Spielberg's attention to detail is impeccable and on the cinematic level the visual contrast of the color tapestry he weaves between United States and East Berlin is sheer poetry in motion. Tom Hanks  and Mark Rylance are superb. Their understanding of the characters and the relationship between them sets the pace for the most outstanding, impressive and remarkable performance. A must see film.

It is not a ‚Äúconspiracy theory‚Äù that Lee Harvey Oswald, one of nine Office of Naval Intelligence fake defectors who went to the USSR in the same month, told ONI‚Äôs Richard Snyder at the American Embassy in Moscow that he was going to reveal the U-2 secrets to the Soviets. text: MY RATING -7 out of 10. Bridge of Spies has the feel an old fashioned drama and has all the hallmarks of a Steven Spielberg film. The attention to detail , the charismatic leading man ( Hanks ) and the sentimentality . There's nothing not to like about this film but is that enough to make it great ? Probably not.  Although Tom Hanks is excellent I think the standout performance is from Mark Rylance who plays the Russian spy , Rudolf Abel . His understated dour acting is brilliant to watch.  If you are expecting an action thriller then you will be disappointed. It's not that type of film. This is pure drama and an enjoyable one at that.

text: I just saw this Spielberg directed flick and it is really well done.  Hanks is great and the story, based on the downing of Frances Gary Powers' U2 spy plane over the Soviet Union in '57 is very accurately done with flawless CGI.  One honest man, the lawyer played by Hanks, is recruited by the CIA to travel to West Berlin and negotiate for the exchange of Powers for a Soviet spy recently captured in the US and named Rudolph Abel.  There is an unexpected wrinkle in the plan when a young American economics graduate student , visiting his girlfriend, gets caught and promptly arrested on the East Berlin side of the wall that the Soviets are erecting at the time to keep the Germans from fleeing over to West Berlin.  The CIA is only interested in getting Powers back before he can tell the Soviets any secret information, but Hanks' character decides that there will be no deal unless he can exchange Abel for both men.  There is a lot of taut negotiating involved and this film will give the viewer a realistic view of the kind of mutual Cold War paranoia that existed at that time as well as the bleak nature of life in West Berlin whose bombed and shot out buildings the Soviets decided would not be rebuilt so they could be a constant reminder to the Germans living there that they had lost WWII.  Anyway, a really interesting flick which should appeal to those interested in the history of the Cold War.
